        "type": "text",
        "text": "Perfect! ✅ Circuit built successfully.\n\n---\n\n## **Wiring Summary**\n\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Pin | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| D2 | Display | a | Segment A (via 220Ω) |\n| D3 | Display | b | Segment B (via 220Ω) |\n| D4 | Display | c | Segment C (via 220Ω) |\n| D5 | Display | d | Segment D (via 220Ω) |\n| D6 | Display | e | Segment E (via 220Ω) |\n| D7 | Display | f | Segment F (via 220Ω) |\n| D8 | Display | g | Segment G (via 220Ω) |\n| D9 | BTN_ADD | a | Add button (pull-up input) |\n| D10 | BTN_SUB | a | Subtract button (pull-up input) |\n| GND | Display | gnd | Ground |\n| GND | BTN_ADD | b | Ground |\n| GND | BTN_SUB | b | Ground |\n\n---\n\n## **How It Works**\n\nThe sketch uses a **7-segment lookup table** to drive digits 0–9. Each button is wired with internal pull-up (HIGH at rest). When pressed, the pin goes LOW—the code detects the HIGH→LOW transition and increments/decrements the counter, clamped to [0, 9]. Debounce delays prevent false triggers.\n\n---\n\n## **Power Budget**\n\n- **Per-pin current**: Each segment ≤ 9 mA (220Ω + typical red LED ≈ 20 mA worst-case, but all 7 segments won't light simultaneously for any digit). Peak segment ≈ 9 mA.\n- **Button pins**: negligible (< 1 mA each).\n- **Total board draw**: < 100 mA (well within Uno's 500 mA USB limit and 200 mA external supply safe zone).\n\n✅ Safe across all constraints."
